What I Learned

CS50’s Introduction to Programming with Scratch officially began today. The first project, Sprites, focused on creating a simple scene using backdrops and multiple sprites. The goal was to get comfortable with the environment and understand how structured building works — step by step.

What Felt Challenging

Scratch is often labeled as a tool for kids. At first glance, it looks simple — almost too simple. That created internal resistance. The hesitation wasn’t about difficulty; it was about ego.

How It Was Overcome

The mindset shifted: if this is where beginners are trained, then this is where foundations are built. Mastery doesn’t start with complexity. It starts with clarity.

Reflection

Today represented humility and a real beginning. Every expert once started with basics — even if those basics looked “too easy.”

This step was small. Very small. But momentum is built exactly like this. Starting small isn’t weakness. It’s discipline.
